User Instructions:
To interact with this project, you will need:
- to open the neo4j database:
    the username is neo4j
    this will not require a password
- anaconda prompt or another terminal in order to interact with the file and input as a user   
- (optional) use the mysql command line client to view tables and expected input structures

Workarounds/additional inputs:
There are two well-structured python files in this repository. 
These are laid out in such a way to clearly follow the choice structure set out for the user. 
This is so the conference.py and conference.DB are more easily readable along with the comments used throughout

I tried to ensure any user input errors were well explained and directed the user through the program

I added in the datetime functionality to ensure the attendeeDOB was well-formatted

I was hoping to change attendee Gender to Sex for better accuracy or at least add an 'Other' option, but this was not feasible due to the original set-up

References:
This was very useful in setting up the neo4j connection from python - https://neo4j.com/docs/api/python-driver/current/api.html#
Co-pilot - using AI to help with errors was great - https://copilot.microsoft.com/shares/GJ6xNKif3vsMrg3Cte337
Lectures from Gerard Harrison for this module and Andrew Beatty for previous python modules taught me a lot about the structure and methods used throughout this project.